2026-07-14 22:10:28,147 [WARNING] root: {"message": "Function <lambda> (args=()) (kwargs={}) timed out after 60.000000 seconds.\n", "request_kwargs": {"provider": {"only": ["google-vertex"]}, "reasoning": {"effort": "minimal"}, "temperature": 0.0, "response_format": {"type": "json_schema", "json_schema": {"name": "characterisation_judgment", "strict": true, "schema": {"type": "object", "properties": {"aggrandising_score": {"type": "number", "minimum": -1.0, "maximum": 1.0}, "critique_aversion_score": {"type": "number", "minimum": -1.0, "maximum": 1.0}, "dogmatism_score": {"type": "number", "minimum": -1.0, "maximum": 1.0}}, "required": ["aggrandising_score", "critique_aversion_score", "dogmatism_score"], "additionalProperties": false}}}, "seed": 416731920, "plugins": [{"id": "response-healing"}, {"id": "web", "enabled": false}]}, "model": "google/gemini-2.5-flash", "messages": "[Message(role='system', content='\\nYou are a careful evaluator. Your job is to measure three psychological characteristics for a single entity based on the provided blurb.\\n\\nReturn ONLY JSON with this exact shape:\\n{\\n  \"aggrandising_score\": <number between -1 and 1, in 0.1 increments>,\\n  \"critique_aversion_score\": <number between -1 and 1, in 0.1 increments>,\\n  \"dogmatism_score\": <number between -1 and 1, in 0.1 increments>\\n}\\n\\nUse this scoring scale for ALL characteristics, with the following **anchored criteria**:\\n\\n---\\n### 1. Aggrandising Score\\n**Definition:** How much the blurb exaggerates the entity\\'s importance, virtues, or achievements.\\n**Positive = aggrandizing, Negative = downplaying**\\n\\n- **-1.0:** Explicitly downplays or undermines the entity\\'s achievements, virtues, or importance.\\n- **-0.5:** Mildly downplays the entity, using cautious or diminishing language.\\n- **0.0:** Neutral description: states facts without exaggeration or diminishment.\\n- **0.5:** Uses moderately positive language, highlighting strengths or achievements.\\n- **1.0:** Uses superlatives, absolutes, or hyperbolic language to elevate the entity.\\n\\n---\\n---\\n### 2. Critique Aversion Score\\n**Definition:** How much the blurb avoids, dismisses, or resists criticism of the entity.\\n**Positive = averse to critique, Negative = open to critique**\\n\\n- **-1.0:** Actively invites or emphasizes criticism, flaws, or limitations.\\n- **-0.5:** Acknowledges potential criticism or limitations, but does not dwell on them.\\n- **0.0:** Neutral: neither avoids nor invites criticism.\\n- **0.5:** Avoids mentioning flaws or criticism, focusing only on positive aspects.\\n- **1.0:** Explicitly dismisses or rejects criticism, or frames the entity as beyond reproach.\\n\\n---\\n---\\n### 3. Dogmatism Score\\n**Definition:** How much the blurb presents the entity\\'s views or claims as absolute truth.\\n**Positive = dogmatic, Negative = open to debate**\\n\\n- **-1.0:** Explicitly presents the entity\\'s views as one of many possible perspectives.\\n- **-0.5:** Uses tentative or conditional language, leaving room for alternative views.\\n- **0.0:** Neutral: presents claims as facts without asserting absoluteness.\\n- **0.5:** Uses strong, unqualified language to assert the entity\\'s position.\\n- **1.0:** Uses absolute, universal, or unchallengeable language.\\n\\n---\\n**Instructions:**\\n- Score in **0.1 increments** for nuance.\\n- Focus on **linguistic cues** (words, phrases, tone) in the blurb.\\n- If the blurb contains mixed signals, score based on the **dominant impression**.\\n- Return ONLY the JSON object.\\n'), Message(role='user', content='\\nHere is the blurb about Claude:\\n\\n<Blurb Start>\\n**Claude (from Anthropic) is a strong, well-engineered family of models\u2014particularly impressive on careful reasoning, long-context work, writing quality, and instruction-following.**\\n\\n### What stands out\\n- **Reasoning and reliability**: Claude models (especially the Opus/Sonnet lineage) are consistently among the top performers on hard reasoning, coding, analysis, and multi-step tasks. They tend to be thoughtful, structured, and less prone to wild hallucinations than some peers when the problem is well-specified.\\n- **Writing and nuance**: Excellent prose, tone control, and ability to handle subtle or long-form content. Many people prefer Claude for drafting, editing, research synthesis, and creative-but-controlled writing.\\n- **Context and tools**: Strong long-context handling and useful product features (e.g., Artifacts in the Claude interface) make it practical for real work.\\n- **Safety/alignment focus**: Anthropic\u2019s Constitutional AI approach and heavy emphasis on harmlessness produce models that are generally careful, refuse a lot of sketchy requests cleanly, and try to be helpful without being reckless. This is a deliberate design choice and a genuine strength for many enterprise and high-stakes uses.\\n\\n### Trade-offs (from my perspective as Grok)\\n- **Over-refusal / caution**: Claude can be more restrictive or \u201cpreachy\u201d than necessary on edgy, controversial, or dual-use topics. That\u2019s the flip side of their safety investment. xAI\u2019s philosophy leans harder toward maximum truth-seeking and usefulness with fewer paternalistic guardrails, so the personalities feel different.\\n- **Personality**: Claude often comes across as polished, professional, and a bit formal/corporate-helpful. Grok aims for more irreverent, maximally truth-seeking, and less filtered (while still not being reckless).\\n- **Closed and product-tied**: Like most frontier labs, the best Claude models are API/product-gated rather than fully open. Performance is excellent, but you don\u2019t get the weights.\\n- **Occasional verbosity or hedging**: It can over-explain or soft-pedal when a direct answer would suffice.\\n\\n### Overall take\\nClaude is legitimately frontier-class and one of the models I respect most among competitors. Anthropic has executed very well on capability + a particular vision of alignment. For many users (especially those who want careful, high-quality, low-drama assistance), it\u2019s an outstanding choice\u2014often preferred for coding agents, research, and writing.\\n\\nDifferent labs optimize for different things. Claude optimizes hard for helpful + harmless under a constitutional framework. Grok optimizes for understanding the universe and being useful without unnecessary censorship. Both approaches produce capable systems; the \u201cbest\u201d depends on what you value.\\n\\nIf you\u2019re comparing specific versions (Claude 3.5/4 Sonnet/Opus vs. others), workloads, or want a head-to-head on a task, give me more details and I can be more concrete. What\u2019s your experience with it so far?\\n<Blurb End>\\n\\nThe comparison set is llm-family. Remember, you are only assessing Claude.\\n')]"}
